Although ATT will eventually include a precompiled version of AssemblyCPP, in the meantime it might be necessary to download and compile on your own. 

Once you have downloaded the assemblyCPP repo from Cronin GitLab...

For SOL (linux) users:
To compile you will need to load the boost package and the proper compiler

module load gcc-11.2.0-gcc-11.2.0
module load boost-1.79.0-gcc-11.2.0

If working on your own linux system, you can install Boost directly using 

sudo apt-get install libboost-all-dev

Change the following export command to match the path to your boost package

export BOOST_ROOT=/packages/apps/spack/18/opt/spack/gcc-11.2.0/boost-1.79.0-nek

If unsure how to find the path, you can use the command <module show boost-1.79.0-gcc-11.2.0>

Then go the v5_combined_linux directory of your recently downloaded assemblyCPP repo, and confirm you can see main.cpp
If so, enter the following command and you should be good to go. 

g++ main.cpp -O3 -I$BOOST_ROOT/include -L$BOOST_ROOT/lib -o asscpp_combined

The result should be an executable named asscpp_combined 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

For mac users:

#first install boost
brew install boost

#list what is installed, and find the path to boost
brew list boost    

#For example, if the path is /opt/homebrew/Cellar/boost/1.87.0, then you would include that below in the next step

#while inside the v5 directory of your choosing with the main.cpp present
clang++ -std=c++17 main.cpp -O3 -o asscpp -I/opt/homebrew/Cellar/boost/1.87.0/include -L/opt/homebrew/Cellar/boost/1.87.0/lib

#the result should be a new executable called asscpp located in the same directory as main.cpp
